EXAMPLE 1. Media outlets are linked by either “hyperlink” or “mention”. Out of your combined data filter these media outlets that are link by “hyperlink” only and by “mention”s. Assign them to new data sets. Lastly, plot them.

HINT: By using activate() we can specify whether we would like to work on the edges or nodes.

media_hyper<-news_media %>% activate(edges) %>% filter(type=="hyperlink")
media_hyper

EXAMPLE 2. Now, please again try to join newly created two data sets. HINT:You can do an operation similar to full join by using the graph_join() function.

media_mention %>% graph_join(media_hyper) %>% plot()
## Joining, by = c("id", "media", "media.type", "type.label", "audience.size")

EXAMPLE 3. You are doing great! In the next step, let’s change the order of our network. HINT: Try using reroute(). It takes usually two arguments, from =… and to=…

media_reversed<-news_media %>% activate(edges)%>%reroute(from = to, to = from)
plot(media_reversed)

GGRAPH - EXERCISES

EXAMPLE 1 Create a ggraph. Use the “news_media” data, color edges in gray, add labels and represent nodes as points

ggraph(news_media) + 
  geom_edge_link(color="gray") + geom_node_text(aes(label = media), repel=TRUE) + geom_node_point()
## Using `stress` as default layout

EXAMPLE 2 Create a new ggraph. Use the “news_media” data, change the color depending on type of links (edges), add labels.

ggraph(news_media) + 
geom_edge_link(aes(color = type)) + 
 geom_node_text(aes(label = media))
## Using `stress` as default layout

EXAMPLE 3 Do you find this graph informative? If not, why? How would you improve it?

ggraph(news_media, layout='linear') + 
  geom_edge_arc(color="gray") + geom_node_text(aes(label = media), repel=TRUE)+ geom_node_point()

CHALLENGE 1 Create a graph that includes also the weight of the edges and contains labels of the nodes.

ggraph(news_media) + 
  geom_edge_link(aes(alpha = weight)) + 
 geom_node_text(aes(label = media))
## Using `stress` as default layout

CHALLENGE 2 As you already know, to measure the importance of the nodes in a particular network one can use centrality functions. Try to find out, which media is central. You can do it in many ways, but try to measure centrality by using the number of edges a node has.

HINT: We introduced you to centrality_degree() and centrality_betweenness(). Plot the centrality using ggraph().

news_media%>%  activate(nodes) %>%
  mutate(centrality = centrality_degree()) %>% arrange(centrality)
## # A tbl_graph: 17 nodes and 49 edges
## #
## # A directed multigraph with 1 component
## #
## # Node Data: 17 × 6 (active)
##   id    media       media.type type.label audience.size centrality
##   <chr> <chr>            <int> <chr>              <int>      <dbl>
## 1 s11   BBC                  2 TV                    34          0
## 2 s09   FOX News             2 TV                    60          1
## 3 s10   ABC                  2 TV                    23          1
## 4 s17   AOL.com              3 Online                33          1
## 5 s13   Google News          3 Online                23          2
## 6 s14   Reuters.com          3 Online                12          2
## # … with 11 more rows
## #
## # Edge Data: 49 × 4
##    from    to type      weight
##   <int> <int> <chr>      <int>
## 1    12    13 hyperlink     22
## 2    12    17 hyperlink     22
## 3    12    16 hyperlink     21
## # … with 46 more rows
news_media%>%  activate(nodes) %>%
  mutate(centrality = centrality_degree())%>% arrange(centrality)%>%
    ggraph() + 
    geom_edge_link() + 
    geom_node_point(aes(size = centrality, colour = centrality))+ geom_node_text(aes(label = media))
## Using `stress` as default layout

FOR FURTHER INTEREST You can describe what type of network your data represent, how many elements it has and add new values to it. HINT: There are functions that allow you to check this information. E.g., have a look at is_directed(). More on structures you can find here: https://michaelgastner.com/DAVisR2021/essentials-of-network-analysis.html#sec:centrality
